04565nam a22007215i 9781487576646DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191995onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875766467 a10.3138/97814875766462doi  a(DE-B1597)536877  a(OCoLC)1129166957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHT352.C22N65 1995 7aSOC0100002bisacsh04a971.6/2251 aMorton, Suzanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIdeal Surroundings :bDomestic Life in a Working-Class Suburb in the 1920s /cSuzanne Morton. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Richmond Heights -- t2. Values and Daily Life -- t3. Elderly Men and Women -- t4. Domestic Responsibilities: Husbands and Wives, Fathers and Mothers -- t5. Single Mothers and Female Household Heads -- t6. Men -- t7. Young Women -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1920s are seen by historians as a crucial period in the formation of the Canadian working class. In Ideal Surroundings, Suzanne Morton looks at a single working-class community as it responded to national and regional changes. Grounded in labour and feminist history, with a strong emphasis on domestic life, this analysis focuses on the relationship between gender ideals and the actual experience of different family members. The setting is Richmond Heights, a working-class suburb of Halifax that was constructed following the 1917 explosion that devastated a large section of the city. The Halifax Relief Commission, specially formed to respond to this incident, generated a unique set of historical records that provides an unusually intimate glimpse of domestic life. Drawing on these and other archives, Morton uncovers many critical challenges to working-class ideals. The male world-view in particular were seriously destabilized as economic transformation and unemployment left many men without the means to support their families, and as the daughters of Richmond Heights increasingly left their class-defined jobs for service and clerical positions. Drawing on recent theoretical and empirical work, Morton expertly combines interpretive and narrative material, creating a vivid portrayal of class dynamics in this critical postwar era. Her focus on the home and domesticity marks and innovative move towards the integration of gender in the study of Canadian history. (Studies in Gender and History)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamilieszNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolezNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aSuburban lifezNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757664640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487576646423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487576646.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK